Add Implicit ARIA Roles to the Date Picker

02

The Listing Detail page template includes a date picker that a user of the CampSpots app could use to book the dates of their trip.

📝 Exercise: Interact with the Date Picker

Before we dive into the code behind the date picker, take a few minutes to interact with it using your keyboard and screen reader.

Can you reach and operate everything? How are the months and dates announced? Is it clear when a date is selected or already booked?

As you go, think about what information would be good to supply with ARIA.

Inspect the Rendered Date Picker in DevTools

Open the Listing Detail page template in the browser and inspect the markup for the date picker.

There are a lot of divs present, most notably for every numbered day on the calendar.

<!-- Excerpt from the rendered date picker HTML --> 
  <div class="date-grid">
    <div class="grid-btn">
			<time date-time="2022-07-31">31</time>
			<span class="icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
		</div>
    <div class="grid-btn  currentMonth">
			<time date-time="2022-08-01">1</time>
			<span class="icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
		</div>
	...

What this tells us is that there isn’t much accessibility information included.

Let’s set about fixing this using a combination of semantic elements and ARIA.

Refactoring the Date Picker

Inside of your editor, open the source code for the date picker at components/date-picker/date-picker.js.

This is a pretty large component that includes a lot of business logic. For our purposes, we’ll focus on the markup in JSX that gets rendered by the browser, which starts around line 71 in the file.

Updating the Month Changers

The first thing to notice is the divs with onClicks added that allow the user to move to the previous and next months on the calendar:

<header>
  <div
    className="btn-month btn-prev"
    disabled={isPrevMonthAvailable() ? '' : 'disabled'}
    onClick={setPrevMonth}
  >
    <span></span>
    { dayjs(activeDate).subtract(1, "month").format("MMM") }
  </div>
  <h4>{ dayjs(activeDate).format("MMMM YYYY") }</h4>
  <div
    className="btn-month btn-next"
    onClick={setNextMonth}
  >
    { dayjs(activeDate).add(1, 'month').format("MMM") }
    <span></span>
  </div>
</header>
<header>
  <div
    className="btn-month btn-prev"
    disabled={isPrevMonthAvailable() ? '' : 'disabled'}
    onClick={setPrevMonth}
  >
    <span></span>
    { dayjs(activeDate).subtract(1, "month").format("MMM") }
  </div>
  <h4>{ dayjs(activeDate).format("MMMM YYYY") }</h4>
  <div
    className="btn-month btn-next"
    onClick={setNextMonth}
  >
    { dayjs(activeDate).add(1, 'month').format("MMM") }
    <span></span>
  </div>
</header>

As we know, divs don’t provide semantic information and they are not keyboard accessible.

Both of these divs should be changed to button elements, which are reachable and operable by default:

// components/date-picker/date-picker.js
<div className="date-picker">
  <header>
      <button
          className="btn-month btn-prev"
          disabled={isPrevMonthAvailable() ? '' : 'disabled'}
          onClick={setPrevMonth}
      >
          <span></span>
          { dayjs(activeDate).subtract(1, "month").format("MMM") }
      </button>
      <h4>{ dayjs(activeDate).format("MMMM YYYY") }</h4>
      <button
          className="btn-month btn-next"
          onClick={setNextMonth}
      >
          { dayjs(activeDate).add(1, 'month').format("MMM") }
          <span></span>
      </button>
  </header>
	...
</div>
// components/date-picker/date-picker.js
<div className="date-picker">
  <header>
      <button

          { dayjs(activeDate).add(1, 'month').format("MMM") }
          <span></span>
      </button>
  </header>
	...
</div>

Save the changes and head back over to the browser.

Inspecting Accessibility Changes in the Browser

Refreshing the browser and inspecting the date picker in DevTools, we see that the month changers are indeed buttons.

Opening the Accessibility Pane in DevTools, we can see that the month buttons now have a role of button:

Implicit ARIA Roles

There are several widget roles in the ARIA specification, including button and link. These roles inform Assistive Technology what the element is and how to interact with it.

When you use certain elements like <button> or <a> in your markup, ARIA roles will be implicitly added. In other words, these elements have accessibility benefits without having to explicitly bolt on a role attribute.
